Thank you, everybody.

00:05:02.404 --> 00:05:05.840
So to get started, I
think the first question

00:05:05.840 --> 00:05:12.006
I'd like to have
us talk about is

00:05:12.006 --> 00:05:14.810
more on the process side of
things, how we approach things.

00:05:14.810 --> 00:05:17.000
And I think we'll
start with Kevin.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:18.420
But I think maybe
multiple people

00:05:18.420 --> 00:05:20.860
will be able to weigh
in just because Google's

00:05:20.860 --> 00:05:24.560
a large company, different
teams do things different ways.

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:26.470
How do teams at
Google decide what

00:05:26.470 --> 00:05:28.629
to build before
actually building it?

00:05:28.629 --> 00:05:31.170
KEVIN DAME: Yeah, so I can talk
a little bit about what we're

00:05:31.170 --> 00:05:33.300
doing on the
Visioning team and how

00:05:33.300 --> 00:05:37.860
we're trying to enhance our
process at YouTube to do that.

00:05:37.860 --> 00:05:41.270
It's a little daunting, because
when I joined Google and joined

00:05:41.270 --> 00:05:44.260
YouTube, I was
interested in evolving

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:45.880
our processes to be better.

00:05:45.880 --> 00:05:48.210
But you have to come in with
a little bit of humility

00:05:48.210 --> 00:05:50.490
because it's a very,
very successful company.

00:05:50.490 --> 00:05:52.865
So you don't want to come in
and say, well, that's wrong.

00:05:52.865 --> 00:05:53.760
What are we doing?

00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:56.240
So had to kind of
think about ways

00:05:56.240 --> 00:05:58.370
to address-- but
also at Google, we

00:05:58.370 --> 00:05:59.937
want to-- I think
part of our culture

00:05:59.937 --> 00:06:01.020
is to keep getting better.

00:06:01.020 --> 00:06:03.340
So people are very open
to, how can we be better?

00:06:03.340 --> 00:06:06.320
So I'll talk about
three things that we

00:06:06.320 --> 00:06:08.830
try to do in the
Visioning team to help.

00:06:08.830 --> 00:06:11.020
And again, we're working
on kind of the early stage.

00:06:11.020 --> 00:06:14.700
So if you think about product
development, which is designing

00:06:14.700 --> 00:06:16.930
and developing and
building a product,

00:06:16.930 --> 00:06:19.980
product vision is kind of the
step before that which is well,

00:06:19.980 --> 00:06:22.360
what should we build before
we start going and building?

00:06:22.360 --> 00:06:24.250
How do we figure out what
the right thing to build is?

00:06:24.250 --> 00:06:25.833
We could build 1,000
different things,

00:06:25.833 --> 00:06:27.520
but what's the
right thing to do?

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:29.510
So I'd say that from
a process perspective

00:06:29.510 --> 00:06:32.140
there's a few things
that we're trying

00:06:32.140 --> 00:06:35.370
to do that are a little bit
different maybe than what

00:06:35.370 --> 00:06:38.170
the norm is in
the tech industry.

00:06:38.170 --> 00:06:41.370
So the first one is we
try to think about-- some

00:06:41.370 --> 00:06:43.234
of this probably sounds obvious.

00:06:43.234 --> 00:06:45.150
But I think when you're
in the thick of things

00:06:45.150 --> 00:06:46.600
it can be very
difficult to do, which

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:48.400
is-- what we try to
do is focus on what's

00:06:48.400 --> 00:06:52.380
the ideal product that we
could get to in a couple years.

00:06:52.380 --> 00:06:54.577
Not four or five years out
because the tech industry

00:06:54.577 --> 00:06:55.160
changes a lot.

00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:57.350
But what's the ideal
experience we can get to.

00:06:57.350 --> 00:06:58.850
That's a little bit
different that I

00:06:58.850 --> 00:07:01.440
think may be more of a lean
approach, which the tech

00:07:01.440 --> 00:07:04.080
industry often uses, which
is let's just build something

00:07:04.080 --> 00:07:07.210
as quickly as possible, get
it out there, and then learn.

00:07:07.210 --> 00:07:08.942
I think that's still
a great philosophy.

00:07:08.942 --> 00:07:10.900
But we want to put just
a little bit more rigor

00:07:10.900 --> 00:07:12.441
in thinking about
what's the thing we

00:07:12.441 --> 00:07:16.440
want to shoot for before
we put something out there.

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:19.091
Second thing is this
idea of-- and it really

00:07:19.091 --> 00:07:20.590
relates to the first
thing as well--

00:07:20.590 --> 00:07:22.389
which is we want to
feel like we have--

00:07:22.389 --> 00:07:24.680
if we are going to put
something out in the marketplace

00:07:24.680 --> 00:07:28.170
and then learn, we feel like
that's kind of an expensive way

00:07:28.170 --> 00:07:29.100
to learn.

00:07:29.100 --> 00:07:31.760
So how can we fail
faster and more often

00:07:31.760 --> 00:07:35.100
internally with rough
prototypes, really quick ways

00:07:35.100 --> 00:07:36.900
to explore many
different things so

00:07:36.900 --> 00:07:38.540
that when we do
converge on something,

00:07:38.540 --> 00:07:39.900
probably take a
little bit longer.

00:07:39.900 --> 00:07:42.066
But then when we converge
on it, our odds of success

00:07:42.066 --> 00:07:42.806
are much higher.

00:07:42.806 --> 00:07:45.430
And the third thing that we try
to do from a process standpoint

00:07:45.430 --> 00:07:48.040
is this idea of Visioning.

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:50.770
You know, I think that
traditionally, sometimes people

00:07:50.770 --> 00:07:53.864
think that it's either like the
leader of the organization who

00:07:53.864 --> 00:07:56.030
creates the vision and then
kind of tells everybody.

00:07:56.030 --> 00:07:59.180
Or sometimes people think, well,
that's a product manager's job.

00:07:59.180 --> 00:08:01.724
What we try to do is
democratize product vision.

00:08:01.724 --> 00:08:03.140
What we try to do
is get everybody

00:08:03.140 --> 00:08:05.114
on the team to participate
in that process

00:08:05.114 --> 00:08:07.030
so that instead of someone
telling them, well,

00:08:07.030 --> 00:08:09.180
here's the vision, now
go design against it,

00:08:09.180 --> 00:08:10.850
everybody on the
team has participated

00:08:10.850 --> 00:08:14.430
and feel like they own
and buy the vision.

00:08:14.430 --> 00:08:18.500
So that's what we try to do on
the Visioning team at YouTube.

00:08:18.500 --> 00:08:20.905
MIKE DENNY: I'm wondering,
Marta, maybe you

00:08:20.905 --> 00:08:22.975
could chime in on
design sprints.

00:08:22.975 --> 00:08:24.350
MARTA REY-BABARRO:
Yeah, totally.

00:08:24.350 --> 00:08:28.630
So I arrived to Google
around three years ago.

00:08:28.630 --> 00:08:30.750
CorpEng UX was a very tiny team.

00:08:30.750 --> 00:08:33.330
We were only four
people in the team.

00:08:33.330 --> 00:08:37.230
And we were redesigning a very
big product, internal product,

00:08:37.230 --> 00:08:39.850
which is the Performance
Evaluation tool.

00:08:39.850 --> 00:08:42.580
The deadlines were crazy.

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:46.230
And there was no time for
design, no time for research.

00:08:46.230 --> 00:08:49.620
And at the time, we had a ton
of meetings, ton of meetings,

00:08:49.620 --> 00:08:52.090
half decisions were
made here, then

00:08:52.090 --> 00:08:54.470
another decision was
made in another meeting.

00:08:54.470 --> 00:08:59.290
So it was a very
difficult process.

00:08:59.290 --> 00:09:01.100
So one of the things
that I thought was,

00:09:01.100 --> 00:09:04.060
why don't we bring
everyone to a room,

00:09:04.060 --> 00:09:06.260
and we make the decisions
that we need to make?

00:09:06.260 --> 00:09:09.910
Let's clear our
agendas for five days.

00:09:09.910 --> 00:09:13.750
And let's give everyone a
voice, engineering-- whoops,

00:09:13.750 --> 00:09:15.280
and it did fall.

00:09:15.280 --> 00:09:15.780
OK.

00:09:15.780 --> 00:09:17.030
MIKE DENNY: We can
still hear you.

00:09:17.030 --> 00:09:17.600
MARTA REY-BABARRO:
You can still hear me?

00:09:17.600 --> 00:09:18.890
OK, great.

00:09:18.890 --> 00:09:21.640
So let's give
Engineering a voice.

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:25.560
There are a lot of engineering
constraints around these tools.

00:09:25.560 --> 00:09:28.680
We are migrating from
old code to a new code,

00:09:28.680 --> 00:09:32.010
so what are the
constraints that we have?

00:09:32.010 --> 00:09:33.240
That designers, as well.

00:09:33.240 --> 00:09:34.670
We had a ton of research done.

00:09:34.670 --> 00:09:36.020
We had business needs.

00:09:36.020 --> 00:09:39.450
So let's give everyone
in the room a voice.

00:09:39.450 --> 00:09:42.810
And once we all know what
is the space in which we

00:09:42.810 --> 00:09:46.220
are designing, then
let's make decisions.

00:09:46.220 --> 00:09:48.270
And it was a gigantic success.

00:09:48.270 --> 00:09:52.320
So from a team of
people in which we

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:55.790
had a very tight deadline,
we were working crazy hours,

00:09:55.790 --> 00:09:58.750
to a process that ended up
being much more organized,

00:09:58.750 --> 00:10:02.300
where features ended up being
built within only five days.

00:10:02.300 --> 00:10:05.330
And everyone was more
in the same page.

00:10:05.330 --> 00:10:09.750
So after that, design
sprinting became a thing--

00:10:09.750 --> 00:10:11.750
like one of the ways,
one of the processes

00:10:11.750 --> 00:10:14.880
that we have internally
to re-design tools,

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:18.960
come up with new tools, come
up with visions for tools,

00:10:18.960 --> 00:10:21.850
think about completely new tools
that don't exist right now.

00:10:21.850 --> 00:10:24.720
And it all starts by
understanding the space

00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:26.771
from everyone's point of view.

00:10:26.771 --> 00:10:27.520
And it's exciting.

00:10:27.520 --> 00:10:29.410
It's a very exciting
way of working.

00:10:29.410 --> 00:10:32.180
Because everyone
feels very energized.

00:10:32.180 --> 00:10:34.670
People don't feel that they
are in just like one space,

00:10:34.670 --> 00:10:35.910
either designing or coding.

00:10:35.910 --> 00:10:39.457
But everyone is in the same
room, making these decisions.

00:10:39.457 --> 00:10:40.290
MIKE DENNY: Awesome.

00:10:40.290 --> 00:10:41.450
Awesome.

00:10:41.450 --> 00:10:47.745
So anyone jump into this.

00:10:47.745 --> 00:10:49.940
This is a broad question
that probably we all

00:10:49.940 --> 00:10:51.760
have an experience with.

